How to choose the best clustering algorithm and the optimal number of clusters?

clValid allows a simultaneous comparison of multiple clustering algorithms in a single function call, to determine the best clustering method and the optimal number of clusters (k)

It calculates 3 indexes for the best separation between clusters:

  • Dunn index
  • Silhouette
  • Connectivity.
# Read data file and Scale

library(dplyr)

rawData = read.csv("/home/sie/wgcna/final_list_degs_annotated.csv", sep = "\t")
row.names(rawData)=rawData$target_id
rawData = as.data.frame(rawData[1:11335,2:29])

# Scale the columns which needs to be the gene names so transpose and put it back
scaled_data <- rawData %>% 
  # transpose the matrix so genes are as columns
  t() %>% 
  # apply scalling to each column of the matrix (genes)
  scale() %>% 
  # transpose back so genes are as rows again
  t()

#####################################################################################
## clValid Functions
#####################################################################################

install.packages("clValid")
library(clValid)

# Choose the algorithms to test
# clValid allow testing 9 different algorithms 

clmethods <- c("hierarchical","kmeans","diana","fanny","som","model","sota","pam","clara")
intern <- clValid(scaled_data, nClust = 3:50,clMethods = clmethods, validation = "internal", maxitems = 11335)

# Summary
summary(intern)

#Plotting
op <- par(no.readonly = TRUE)
par(mfrow = c(2, 2), mar = c(4, 4, 3, 1))

plot(intern, legend = FALSE)
plot(nClusters(intern), measures(intern, "Dunn")[, , 1], type = "n",axes = F, xlab = "", ylab = "")
legend("center", clusterMethods(intern), col = 1:9, lty = 1:9,pch = paste(1:9))
Optimal Scores:

             Score     Method       Clusters
Connectivity 2651.2583 hierarchical 3       
Dunn            0.1019 hierarchical 26      
Silhouette      0.1934 kmeans       7
Recall that the connectivity should be minimized, while both the Dunn index and the silhouette width should be maximized. So, based on these indices, the hierarchical clustering with k = 26 best suits our data. 
# Calculate the distance between each gene (rows)
dist_mat <-  dist(scaled_data, method = 'euclidean')

#choose the best linkage method
hclust_aver <- hclust(dist_mat, method = "average" )
plot(hclust_aver, labels = F, hang = -1)

hclust_single <- hclust(dist_mat, method = "single" )
plot(hclust_single, labels = F, hang = -1)

hclust_centroid <- hclust(dist_mat, method = "centroid" )
plot(hclust_centroid, labels = F, hang = -1)

hclust_median <- hclust(dist_mat, method = "median" )
plot(hclust_median, labels = F, hang = -1)

hclust_mcquitty <- hclust(dist_mat, method = "mcquitty" )
plot(hclust_mcquitty, labels = F, hang = -1)

hclust_compl <- hclust(dist_mat, method = "complete" )
plot(hclust_compl, labels = F, hang = -1)

hclust_ward.d <- hclust(dist_mat, method = "ward.D" )
plot(hclust_ward.d, labels = F, hang = -1)


# Cut the tree
cut_comp <- cutree(hclust_ward.d, k = 26)
library(dendextend)

# Color the branches of dendogram
avg_dend_obj <- as.dendrogram(hclust_ward.d)
avg_col_dend <- color_branches(avg_dend_obj,  k = 26)
plot(avg_col_dend)

We choose the ward.D linkage method as the most appropriate for our data
